    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1959-08-17T19:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1959-08-17T19:00:00-05:00" n="98"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d98">
                <head>98. Message From the <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">President</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d98fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 371.04/8–1759. Confidential; Priority. Transmitted in <gloss
                            target="#t_Cahto1">Cahto</gloss> 16 from Santiago, which is the source
                        text.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Santiago</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1959-08-17T20:00:00-04:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 17, 1959—8 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Dear Mr. President</hi>: All over but the shouting.
                    Tomorrow will wind it up and we leave early Wednesday,<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d98fn2">August 19.</note> returning to Washington late that night.
                    On balance, I feel the conference was very successful. The three proposals which
                    we were the first to initiate in general terms<note n="3" xml:id="d98fn3"
                        >Reference is to Secretary <persName corresp="#p_HCA1">Herter</persName>’s
                        address before the second plenary session, August 13; see <ref target="#d94"
                            >Document 94</ref>.</note> were all reduced to concrete, satisfactory
                    resolutions. The Cuban case, while skillfully handled by Foreign Minister
                        <persName corresp="#p_RGR1">Roa</persName>, was overdone and created adverse
                    opinion. From now on <persName corresp="#p_CRF1">Castro</persName> is going to
                    be watched by all the American states with whom he lost much ground by stating
                    this conference was nothing but a great conspiracy against him and by sending
                    here his brother, <persName corresp="#p_RGR1">Raul</persName>, who,
                    incidentally, is still hung up in Peru. <persName corresp="#p_RRRJ1"
                        >Rubottom</persName>, who has wide experience in conferences such as this,
                    feels that the after effects will last for a long time and be very salutary.
                    However, it will be good to get home.</p>
                <p>Faithfully yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="strong">Chris</hi>
                        </persName>
                        <note n="4" xml:id="d98fn4">
                            <gloss target="#t_Cahto1">Cahto</gloss> 16 bears this typed
                            signature.</note>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
